  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some AngularJS interview questions?",
  "response": "When preparing for an AngularJS interview, candidates can expect a range of questions that test their understanding of the framework, its concepts, and how to apply them in practical scenarios. Below are some common AngularJS interview questions along with brief explanations:\n\n1. **What is AngularJS?**\n   - AngularJS is a structural framework for dynamic web applications. It allows developers to use HTML as the template language and extends HTML's syntax to express an application's components clearly and succinctly.\n\n2. **Explain the concept of two-way data binding in AngularJS.**\n   - Two-way data binding means that any updates to the view are immediately reflected in the model and vice-versa. This leads to less boilerplate and more straightforward code.\n\n3. **What is a scope in AngularJS?**\n   - Scope is an object that refers to the application model. It acts as a glue between the controller and the view and allows for data binding.\n\n4. **What are directives in AngularJS?**\n   - Directives are markers on DOM elements (such as elements, attributes, CSS, etc.) that tell the AngularJS's HTML compiler to attach a specified behavior to that DOM element. Examples include `ng-model`, `ng-bind`, and custom directives.\n\n5. **Can you explain the concept of services in AngularJS?**\n   - Services are singleton objects or functions used for organizing and sharing code across the app. These can be built-in services like $http or custom services defined by the developer.\n\n6. **What role does the `$http` service play in AngularJS?**\n   - The `$http` service is used for making AJAX calls to obtain data from servers. It returns a promise object, which allows handling asynchronous requests.\n\n7. **Explain `$watch` in AngularJS.**\n   - `$watch` is a scope method that allows watching for changes in scope properties. It triggers a callback whenever the watched variable changes.\n\n8. **What is the difference between `$scope` and `scope` in directives?**\n   - `$scope` is available in controllers and holds the application data/model. Conversely, `scope` in directives is used to define an isolate scope for the directive, helping to control what properties the directive can access.\n\n9. **How can you share data between controllers in AngularJS?**\n   - Data can be shared between controllers using services, factories, or by placing the data on the `$rootScope`.\n\n10. **What is dependency injection in AngularJS?**\n    - Dependency injection is a design pattern that AngularJS uses to manage how components are wired together. This allows injecting a required service into a component and helps manage the dependent objects.\n\n11. **Describe the digest cycle in AngularJS.**\n    - The digest cycle is the process AngularJS uses to watch for changes in the application and update the view accordingly. It checks for changes to model values and propagates the changes from the model to the view and vice-versa.\n\n12. **What is a custom directive in AngularJS and how is it created?**\n    - A custom directive is a user-defined directive in AngularJS that can be used to extend HTML. It is created using the `directive` function and can be used to simplify or enhance the DOM manipulation.\n\n13. **Describe the purpose of `$apply` in AngularJS.**\n    - `$apply` is used to execute an expression in Angular's digest cycle. It may be necessary when a model is updated outside of AngularJS's scope (e.g., in a DOM event listener).\n\n14. **What are `ng-repeat` and `ng-if` used for in AngularJS?**\n    - `ng-repeat` is used to iterate over a collection and generate DOM elements for each item. `ng-if` is a directive that conditionally displays or hides elements based on a boolean expression.\n\n15. **Explain `$digest` and `$apply` in AngularJS.**\n    - `$digest` processes all the watches and evaluates the watch expressions. `$apply` is a method used to execute code and then call the `$digest` cycle to update the bindings.\n\nTailor your preparation based on your experience and the specific role you\u2019re applying for, as questions can vary widely in complexity and focus.",
  "response_tokens": [
